# Character Profile: Atom

## Character Background

Steve Reeves once captivated America as a charismatic movie star in the 1950s, famed for portraying the superhero Atom in popular black-and-white serials. His films painted him as a larger-than-life hero, but away from the silver screen, Steve's life was complex and troubled. During the Red Scare, Steve's associations with known socialists and communists brought intense scrutiny. In a moment of fear, he publicly denounced several friends to save his career, an act that led to his social and professional downfall. Disgraced and isolated, Steve's life spiraled downward, ending in a mysterious death rumored to be either murder or suicide.

Decades later, fifth-dimensional alien beings—unable to comprehend three-dimensional life and death—intercepted reruns of his films. Mistaking these for actual historical records, they resurrected Atom, believing Steve to be the real hero. Using advanced technology, they encased Steve's essence in a reality-warping cocoon, reconstructing him based on their interpretation of the broadcasts.

When Steve awoke, he found himself not only alive but transformed. He now physically embodies the black-and-white aesthetic of his old films, with his appearance shifting more towards monochrome under stress or during heroic actions. Additionally, Steve's memories are a confusing blend of his real life and the scripted adventures of Atomic, causing him frequent identity crises.

